I have a bunch of 'Car' documents in my MongoDB, each of them having some cars with details within them. My code reads every 'Car' document and inserts the cars  with their respective Year, Name, Colour etc as a row into a worksheet before writing a new excel file for each 'Car'. The code is as below (I have removed some code for better readability but the workflow is the same):

````javascript

var createExcel = (d) => {
  var workbook = new Excel.Workbook();
  workbook.xlsx.readFile('certificate.xlsx').then(function() {
    var worksheet = workbook.getWorksheet();

    var rows = []
    var carName = d.name
    var year = d.year
      // Declare some other variables which store properties of the document

    for (let i = 0; i < d.cars.length; i++) {
      rows.push(['', carName, year, ... ])
    }
    for (let j = 0; j < rows.length; j++) {
      worksheet.spliceRows(18, 0, rows[j]); //Add all rows after skipping the first 18 rows
    }

    workbook.xlsx.writeFile('Car' + carName + '.xlsx').then(console.log("Done")).catch(e => console.log(e))
  })
}

Cars.find(function(error, data) {
  if (error) {
    console.log(error)
  } else {
    for (let f = 0; f < 500; f++) {
      createExcel(data[f])
    }
  }
})
````

Post some digging around, I realised that the Zero byte File issue occurred only when there were a lot of 'Cars'. My code works perfectly fine as long as I run it with <= 500 'Cars' at a time. 

The more Cars I try and run through this, the slower it gets and in some cases just does not resolve at all (Or maybe it is that the program is taking a lot of time to write these files but I end up exiting it before it finishes. The longest I left the program running is overnight (~7-8 hours) with ~6000 car documents. Got all Zero byte files the next morning )

Another thing I noticed is that since it's a Promise, I had to wait a little. The file at first shows up as  a Zero byte file and then when it's finally written gets the appropriate file size. The wait time is dependent on how heavy or how many files you're writing.

Why does the process of writing slow down so much beyond 500 files is still confusing me. I tried running the same program with 600 Cars and it is extremely slow, taking at least 20 minutes to write the files. Same program with 500 works like a charm and will usually write those 500 files in about a minute or so. 

Any help or information will be appreciated :) @guyonroche
